  "text": "The ability to detect and quantify proteins that are predictors of susceptibility (and/or progression or efficacy of treatments) 1 in specific local tissue prior to clinical detection will be immensely helpful to control various disease states. The follow up value for such proteins in late onset, progressive, multifactorial or metastatic diseases is immense. The diagnosis using blood or excretory fluids based detection of such proteins is often proven unsuitable due to release of the protein in fluids by multiple organs. Only the local tissue protein content often serves as a true predictor of the given disease or disorder 1, [CITATION_1] . Glaucoma refers to a group of late onset, progressive and irreversible blinding diseases where loss of sight occurs without any other previous symptom or pain. In most individuals a significant degree of peripheral vision is lost before the loss is realized. Intervention usually delays its further progression. Glaucoma is frequently associated with elevation in intraocular pressure (IOP). IOP is the only modifiable factor that confers neuroprotection against glaucomatous vision loss even in the glaucoma patients where the IOP is within the normal pressure range (termed normal tension glaucoma) 3 . The trabecular meshwork (TM) is a tiny region in the anterior chamber that undergoes pathologic changes contributing to impeded aqueous humor outflow and consequent IOP elevation.",
